            "details": "<p data-start=\"178\" data-end=\"629\">Yet <em>Baḥr-i Hind</em>: it also has another name, <em>Baḥr-i Aḫḍar</em> (the Green Sea). Its eastern side borders the lands of <em>Ṣīn</em> (China), and its northern side adjoins the fertile regions of <em>Hind</em> (India). Its western side reaches the lands of Yemen, but its southern extent is unknown to far-seeing minds, and as it stretches onward, it passes by the <em>Cezīre-i Serendīb</em> (the Island of Serendib; modern Sri Lanka). It is reported that in the <em>Baḥr-i Ṣīn</em> (the China Sea), which is connected to the Indian Ocean, there are one thousand seven hundred inhabited islands, each with abundant populations. Besides these, it is said that the uninhabited islands are innumerable and beyond all reckoning. In general, another name of the <em>Deryā-yı Hind</em> (Indian Ocean) is <em>Baḥr-i Zenc</em> (the Sea of the Zanj/Africans), for the lands of <em>Zenc</em> (Zanj, the East African coast) lie to its south, and thus it came to be called the Sea of Zanj. It is connected to the <em>Baḥr-i Muḥīṭ</em> (the Great Ocean / the surrounding ocean).</p>\r\n<p data-start=\"1248\" data-end=\"1547\">There is no sea whose waves, surges, and tumults make such terrifying and astonishing noises. However, it does not foam, nor does its sand crack upon contact; otherwise, ships could never pass through that sea. Waves of that kind have been described as <em>mevc-i mecnūn</em> (crazy waves)... [partial translation]</p>",
